The clay material, which contained a naturally occurring aluminosilicate layer, is a Halloysite nanotube (HNTs) which is surrounded by multiple alumina/silica layers. In HNTs, the aluminol groups (Al-OH) are present on an internal surface, whereas the external surface contains siloxane groups (Si-O-Si). The presence of such a functional group in HNTs-layered- structure creates a positive charge in an internal layer, whereas negative charge on the external surface. Resultant, this uniqueness in HNTs layered structure provides a large surface area, high porosity, rapid migration of ions, and fast charging/discharging capability. Furthermore, the novel structures of HNTs have a high interest in its surface modification and novel applications such as adsorption, bone implantation, and drug delivery. Additionally, the large porosity and surface area make HNTs an appropriate candidate for energy storage device fabrication [54]. Motivated by this phenomenon, Doong et al. have fabricated composite material based on the combination of GQDs and HNTs for high-performance supercapacitor applications [42]. This nanocomposite was synthesized in the presence of (3-aminopropyl)-triethoxysilane (APTES) for amide linkage formation with GQDs-HNTs (Fig. 1
                     ). The presence of amide linkage provides the active site for charge storage and allows its transportation for application as supercapacitor. Within the current densities of the order of 0.5–20 A g
                     −1, the above nanocomposite showed specific capacitances in the range of 363–216 Fg−1.
